  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a global issue with varying legal approaches across different nations. Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) framework\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Patriot Act provides extensive regulatory mechanisms\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Significant criminal penalties\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified approach through EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Emphasizes customer due diligence\n- Centralized beneficial ownership registers\n- Risk-based approach to prevention\n- Harmonized legal standards across member states\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA)\n- Sophisticated regulatory framework\n- Strong focus on financial intelligence\n- Robust reporting mechanisms\n- Significant emphasis on corporate liability\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Traditionally known for banking secrecy\n- Gradually implementing stricter international standards\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n- Cooperative with international investigations\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict government oversight\n- Increasing international compliance\n- Severe criminal penalties\n\nEach jurisdiction has unique characteristics, but international cooperation is increasingly important in combating money laundering.",
